SIMPLE: phlegmatic
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Phlegmatic
<hw>Phleg*mat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>phlegmaticus</ets>, Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>phlegmatique</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Watery.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Aqueous and
<xex>phlegmatic</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir I. Newton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Abounding in phlegm; <as>as, <ex>phlegmatic</ex>
humors; a <ex>phlegmatic</ex> constitution.</as></def>
<rj><au>Harvey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Generating or causing phlegm.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Cold and
<xex>phlegmatic</xex> habitations.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir T.
Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not easily excited to action or passion; cold; dull;
sluggish; heavy; <as>as, a <ex>phlegmatic</ex> person</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Phlegmatic temperament</b></col> <fld>(Old
Physiol.)</fld>, <cd>lymphatic temperament. See under
<er>Lymphatic</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phlegmatical</ent>⟦br⟧
